solution:
Since $(x-y)(x+y) = (x-y)^2$, we can write the system of equations as: \begin{align*}
(x-y)(x+y) &= 12, \\
(x-y)^2 &= 36.
\end{align*}Then we have: \begin{align*}
(x-y)(x+y) &= (x-y)^2, \\
12 &= 36.
\end{align*}We can subtract the first equation from the second to find the value of $x+y$: \begin{align*}
0 &= 36 - 12, \\
0 &= 24.
\end{align*}This implies that $x+y = 0$, so $y = -x$. Substituting this into the first equation, we find that $x = 2$ and $y = -2$. Therefore, the value of $y$ is $\boxed{-2}$.

original_problem:
The first three stages of a pattern are shown below, in which each line segment represents a toothpick. If the pattern continues such that at each successive stage, three toothpicks are added to the previous arrangement, how many toothpicks are necessary to create the arrangement for the 250th stage? [asy]
size(150);
defaultpen(linewidth(0.7));
void drawSquare(pair A){

draw((A.x + 0.1,A.y)--(A.x + 0.9,A.y));

draw((A.x,A.y + 0.1)--(A.x,A.y + 0.9));

draw((A.x + 1,A.y + 0.1)--(A.x + 1,A.y + 0.9));

draw((A.x + 0.1,A.y + 1)--(A.x + 0.9,A.y + 1));
}

int k = 0;

for(int i = 1; i <= 3; ++i){

for(int j = 0; j < i; ++j){

drawSquare((k,0));

++k;

}

draw((k+0.1,0.5)--(k+0.9,0.5),EndArrow);

++k;
}
label("$\cdots$",(k,0.5));
[/asy]

problem:
The first three stages of a pattern are shown below, in which each line segment represents a toothpick.  If the pattern continues such that at each successive stage, the number of toothpicks is triple the number used in the previous stage, how many toothpicks are necessary to create the arrangement for the 8th stage? [asy]
size(200);
defaultpen(linewidth(0.7));
pair A,B,C,D,E,F));
A=(1,1.5);
B=(0,0);
C=(3,0);
D=(2,-2);
E=(0,-1);
F=(3,-1);
draw(B--C--D--E--F--B,linewidth(0.7));
draw((1,0.3)--(1,-0.3),linewidth(0.7));
draw((2,0.3)--(2,-0.3),linewidth(0.7));
draw((2,-0.5)--(2,-1.5),linewidth(0.7));

draw((4,1.5)--(3,1.5)--(2,0)--(1,1.5),linewidth(0.7));
draw((4,1)--(3,1)--(2,0)--(1,1),linewidth(0.7));
draw((5,1.5)--(5,0)--(6,0)--(6,1.5),linewidth(0.7));
draw((5,1)--(5,0)--(6,0)--(6,1),linewidth(0.7));

draw((7,1.5)--(6,1.5)--(5,1)--(4,1.5),linewidth(0.7));
draw((7,1)--(6,1)--(5,1)--(4,1),linewidth(0.7));
draw((8,1.5)--(8,0)--(9,0)--(9,1.5),linewidth(0.7));
draw((8,1)--(8,0)--(9,0)--(9,1),linewidth(0.7));

draw((1,0)--(2,0),endArrow(6));
draw((3,0)--(4,0),endArrow(6));
draw((5,0)--(6,0),endArrow(6));
draw((7,0)--(8,0),endArrow(6));
draw((9,0)--(10,0),endArrow(6));

label("$1$ toothpick",(1,-0.5));

label("$3$ toothpicks",(3,-0.5));

label("$9$ toothpicks",(5,-0.5));

label("$27$ toothpicks",(7,-0.5));

label("$81$ toothpicks",(9,-0.5));

[/asy]

original_problem:
I have a picture with dimensions $x$ and $y$ (in inches), such that $x$ and $y$ are both integers greater than one. I would like to place this picture in an elongated frame of dimensions $(2x + 3)$ and  $(y+2)$. If I measured the area of the frame to be $34$ square inches, what is the area of the picture in square inches? (Note that by "the area of the frame," we mean the shaded region shown below).  [asy]
size(5cm);
defaultpen(linewidth(0.7));
real eps=0.2;
filldraw((0,0)--(2,0)--(2,1)--(0,1)--cycle,gray);
filldraw((0,0)+(eps,eps)--(2,0)+(-eps,eps)--(2,1)+(-eps,-eps)--(0,1)+(eps,-eps)--cycle,white);
label("picture",(1,0.5));
label("frame",(1,1-eps/2));
[/asy]

problem:
In the diagram, the triangle has an area of $60$ square units. What is the area of triangle $ABC$? [asy]
defaultpen(linewidth(0.7));
pair A=(0,0), B=(9,0), C=(0,6.5);
draw((-2,0)--A, EndArrow);
draw((-2,0)--B, EndArrow);
draw((-2,0)--C, EndArrow);
draw(A--B, EndArrow);
draw(A--C, EndArrow);
draw(B--C, EndArrow);
label("A", A, SW);
label("B", B, SE);
label("C", C, N);
label("$x$", A--B, S);
label("$x$", A--C, SW);
label("$6x$", B--C, E);
label("$120^\circ$", A, N);
[/asy]
